Project Update — Week 11
Data Sources
For this phase of the project I decided to work with three datasets from FRED (Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis), which is one of the most reliable and well-documented sources of U.S. economic data. All three are freely available with no account required and have clear documentation pages.

Median Sales Price of Houses Sold (MSPUS) | Quarterly, 1963–2025 | Series page | Source: U.S. Census Bureau and HUD. Tracks the median sale price of newly constructed homes across the U.S.
Real Median Household Income (MEHOINUSA646N) | Annual, 1984–2024 | Series page | Source: U.S. Census Bureau, Current Population Survey. Inflation-adjusted so I can make meaningful comparisons over time.
30-Year Fixed Mortgage Rate (MORTGAGE30US) | Weekly, 1971–2026 | Series page | Source: Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey.

I originally planned to also use the NAR Housing Affordability Index (FIXHAI) from FRED, but ran into a roadblock: it is copyright-restricted by the National Association of Realtors and FRED is only legally allowed to distribute the last 13 months of it. Rather than rely on a pre-built index I couldn't fully access or inspect, I decided to construct my own affordability measures from the three series above. This ended up being a better approach analytically because I can be fully transparent about exactly how the measures are calculated and what assumptions they rest on.
Data Acquisition
All three datasets were downloaded as CSV files directly from their FRED series pages at no cost and with no account required. One thing I ran into: FRED defaults to showing only the last 13 months of data in its download window, so I had to manually change the date range in the graph view on each series page before hitting download. Once I figured that out, getting the full historical records was straightforward.
Strengths and Limitations
What these datasets can answer:

How have home prices grown relative to income over time at the national level?
How has the monthly cost of carrying a mortgage changed as a share of household income?
How do periods of high interest rates like the early 1980s or 2022 to 2024 interact with home prices to affect affordability?
How does affordability today compare to historical norms going back to the 1980s?

What they cannot answer:

Regional variation. All three series are national aggregates, so a family in rural Iowa and a family in San Francisco look identical in this data. This is a significant limitation given my original research questions were city-level. I may need to bring in Zillow or ACS data later to address this.
Renter affordability. MSPUS covers new home sales only, meaning renters who make up about 35% of U.S. households are entirely absent from this analysis.
Existing home market. MSPUS tracks new construction only, not the much larger resale market. New homes tend to skew higher-end, so my affordability measures may be slightly more pessimistic than what the typical buyer actually faces.
Within-group inequality. The median income figure hides the full distribution. Affordability could be worsening badly for lower-income households even while the median looks stable.
Down payment barriers. My affordability calculation assumes a 20% down payment, which is increasingly unrealistic for first-time buyers and doesn't capture that barrier at all.
Demographics. There is no way to break these series down by race, age, or household type, which are all important dimensions of the housing crisis.

What I Learned from Exploratory Analysis
The first challenge I encountered was that the three series have completely different frequencies. Home price is quarterly, income is annual, and mortgage rate is weekly, so I couldn't just merge them directly. I had to resample the mortgage rate down to quarterly averages and forward-fill the annual income into quarterly observations before I could combine them into a single dataset covering 1984 to 2024.
From there I constructed two affordability metrics from scratch:
Price-to-income ratio is home price divided by annual income. The standard rule of thumb is that homes should cost no more than 3x annual income. Looking at this over time shows the ratio has risen well above that benchmark since the mid-2000s and has not come back down.
Monthly payment-to-income ratio uses the standard mortgage amortization formula assuming 20% down and a 30-year fixed loan to calculate what share of monthly income the mortgage payment on the median home would consume each quarter. The conventional threshold is 28% and above that is considered cost-burdened. This metric captures something the price-to-income ratio misses: even when home prices are flat, a sharp rise in interest rates can push monthly payments well above what families can afford. This is clearly visible in the early 1980s and again after 2022.
The most striking chart was the one that indexed all three series to 1984 = 100. Home prices have grown dramatically faster than income over the full period, and the gap widened sharply after 2020. Mortgage rates declined for most of the period before spiking back up recently, which had been partially offsetting the price increases until it stopped doing so.
Cleaning and Wrangling
Completed so far:

